title: selena_schiess
body:
Selena Fiona Schiess is fan made characters of RWBY, a 3DCG series produced by Rooster Teeth.


h4. Abilities
Selena's style is comparable to a spider waiting for its prey to fall into its web. As Selena is blind, she cannot rely on her vision in combat. Instead, she uses her sense of hearing, touch, smell and Semblance usage to fight.
Passively, Selena is able to “see” small disturbances in a electromagnetic field similar to the electrolocation used by sharks when hunting prey. 

She wields a simple yet high quality [[glaive (polearm)|]]. 

h4. Physical characteristics
Selena has pale alice blue eyes and long bleached white hair. Selena is legally blind with 95% vision loss in both eyes and in addition, possesses a weak right arm that is constantly in pain.

She stands 6'0 tall.

h4. Attire
She usually wears skimpy black corset and a pair of hot-pants which accentuate her figure, full sleeved black coat and her exo-skeleton arm upgraded with razor claws, enhanced mobility, and tighter grip strength.

title: meruem
body:
Character from [[Hunter x Hunter]]. Meruem is the main antagonist of the [i]Chimera Ants[/i] arc.

[spoiler]The most powerful offspring of the [[Chimera Ant Queen]], and the King of the Chimera Ants. Meruem was initially seen as a cruel and violent leader. The Queen's intention to give birth to a perfect offspring was reflected in Meruem's mentality, with the Ant being haughty towards all. He spoke in an eloquent manner and had refined tastes for one of his species. However, as the story progresses, Meruem starts to grudgingly respect [[komugi_(hunter_x_hunter)|Komugi]], a human girl. He eventually even grows to care for her. From there on, Meruem begins to question the differences between the Ants and mankind. He battles with his identity as a half-human and half-insect, questioning the nature of violence and strength as true power. Meruem initially considers humans as nothing more than livestock to be farmed, however, through his interactions with Komugi, and after his fight against Netero, Meruem begins to see humans as incredible beings with  immense potential through their tenacity for breaking their own limits. 

According to his own mother, his name means the "light that illuminates all."
[/spoiler]

h4. Appearance

Meruem has light [[green skin]], [[purple eyes]], and is [[toned]]. He has a large purple shell-like armor over his head that resembles a helmet. There are dark purple pigmented areas on his arms, legs, chest, and head. Meruem is always [[barefoot]]. He also possessed a large [[tail]] equipped with a [[stinger]] that serves as his weapon. Both his hands and feet had only [[fewer_digits|four digits]] each. He wears a dark [[green_jacket|green]] [[cropped jacket]].

Meruem shares traits and personality with some of the main villains from the [[Dragon Ball]] series. Meruem's body vaguely resembles Frieza's with the purple color scheme (namely, the deltoids and shins). Meruem's appearance is also similar to Cell's (in particular his hands, tail & color scheme of green & purple).

h4. External links

title: siberia
body:
Siberia (/saɪˈbɪəriə/; Russian: Сибирь, tr. Sibir', IPA: [sʲɪˈbʲirʲ] (listen)) is an extensive geographical region, constituting all of North Asia, from the Ural Mountains in the west to the Pacific Ocean in the east. It has been a part of Russia since the latter half of the 16th century, after the Russians conquered lands east of the Ural Mountains. Siberia is vast and sparsely populated, covering an area of over 13.1 million square kilometres (5,100,000 sq mi), but home to merely one-fifth of Russia's population. Novosibirsk and Omsk are the largest cities in the region.

Because Siberia is a geographic and historic region and not a political entity, there is no single precise definition of its territorial borders. Traditionally, Siberia extends eastwards from the Ural Mountains to the Pacific Ocean, and includes most of the drainage basin of the Arctic Ocean. The river Yenisey divides Siberia into two parts, Western and Eastern. Siberia stretches southwards from the Arctic Ocean to the hills of north-central Kazakhstan and to the northern parts of Mongolia and China. The central part of Siberia (West and East Siberian economic regions) was considered the core part of the region in the Soviet Union. Beyond the core, Siberia's western part includes some territories of the Ural region, and the far eastern part has been historically called the Russian Far East.

Siberia is known worldwide primarily for its long, harsh winters, with a January average of −25 °C (−13 °F). It is geographically situated in Asia; however, due to it being colonized and incorporated into Russia, it is culturally and politically a part of Europe. European cultural influences, specifically Russian, predominate throughout the region, due to it having had Russian emigration from Europe since the 16th century, forming the Siberian Russian sub-ethnic group.[Over 85% of the region's population is of European descent.

title: samurai_jack
body:
[b]Samurai Jack[/b] is an American action-adventure comedy animated television series created by Genndy Tartakovsky for [[Cartoon Network]]. The series follows "[[samurai jack (character)|Jack]]", an unnamed [[samurai]] sent through time to a dystopian future ruled by the tyrannical shape-shifting demon, [[Aku (samurai jack)|]]. Jack quests to travel back in time and defeat Aku before he can take over the world.

The series premiered on August 10, 2001, ending in its fourth season on September 25, 2004, without concluding the story. A revival was produced twelve years later, giving the fifth and final season that concludes the series, which premiered on [[Adult Swim]]'s [[Toonami]] block on March 11, 2017.

body:
An extinct animal that lived during the Cambrian period (544-500 million years ago). It had a head with prominent eyes and a pair of grasping appendages, and its body was flanked by lobes used for swimming. The largest predator of the time period, it could grow as long as 2 meters (6 feet) in length and was widely distributed. Its name means "strange shrimp."

title: matara_okina
body:
[b]The Ultimate, Absolute Secret God[/b]

[[Touhou]] character introduced as the stage 6 boss and extra stage boss in [[Hidden Star in Four Seasons]].

She has [[long_hair|long]], [[blonde_hair|blonde]] hair and [[yellow eyes]]. She wears a [[tabard]] with [[constellation print]] accompanied by a [[green skirt]] and [[boots]]. Her clothes feature [[long_sleeves|long]] and [[wide_sleeves|wide]] sleeves. Her Stage 6 portrait depicts her suspending a [[drum]] in [[floating object|midair]] while [[sitting]] on a [[chair]]; [[Touhou Sangetsusei]] subsequently depicts her sitting in a [[wheelchair]]. She is also depicted with a flaming [[aura]]. Her [[hat]] has three points.

Okina is a hidden god with a wide range of public faces, those being an Earth mother goddess, a god of noh, a god of stars, a god of silkworm breeding, a god of hindrances, a god of discriminated peoples, et cetera. As one of the Sages of Gensoukyou, she protects Gensoukyou from the Outside World. Her servants are [[Teireida Mai]] and [[Nishida Satono]]. She is based on Matarajin, a Buddhist deity. Her abilities let her create doors on the back of anything, hence she is sometimes depicted in fanworks with [[door]]s.

She bears a striking resemblance to [[Junko (touhou)|]] from [[Legacy of Lunatic Kingdom]], and her abilities and position are similar to those of [[Yakumo Yukari]].

Matarajin is sometimes conflated with Hata no Kawakatsu (alluded to in-game via her comments on [[Eternity Larva]] and her status as a God of Noh), which has led some fanworks to depict Okina as being close to [[Toyosatomimi no Miko]] and [[Hata no Kokoro]].

h4. External links

* "Touhou Wiki: Okina Matara":https://en.touhouwiki.net/wiki/Okina_Matara

title: baldr_force
body:
A [[science fiction]] visual novel with [[mecha]] action gameplay in the [[Baldr (series)|]] series. It is the first Baldr game to feature a [[cyberpunk]] setting, where characters dive into a virtual reality world to conduct leisure, business, and military operations. This type of setting would become a mainstay feature of the Baldr franchise, with later entries building upon the VR themes introduced in this game.

Originally released in 2002 for PC, it received a rerelease with an updated soundtrack titled [b]Baldr Force EXE[/b] in 2003, which received an all-ages [[Sega Dreamcast]] port in 2004, and a [[PlayStation 2]] port with a new voice cast in 2005. The PS2 version was later ported back to PC as [b]Baldr Force Standard Edition[/b] in 2007. A four-episode OVA adaptation of the game titled [[Baldr Force EXE Resolution]] was released between 2006 and 2007.

title: hugo_andore
body:
[b]Hugo Andore[/b] is a [[Capcom]] character from the [[Street Fighter]] videogame series. However, his first appearance was in another game called [[Final Fight]].

Hugo appeared first as part of the original [[Mad Gear]] gang that terrorized the streets of Metro City in [[Final Fight I]]. 

The Andore family (pronounced An-Do-Ray as in André) is a clan of German pro wrestlers modeled after the real life wrestler [[Andre the Giant|André the Giant]]. They are also the strongest underlings in the Final Fight series. While it is clear Hugo is a member of the Andore family and Capcom has stated he appears in Final Fight, it is unclear if he's the original Andore, Andore Jr. or another family member entirely. However, there is evidence that point to him being the first Andore (who wears lavender) and Andore Jr. (who wears red) being his brother. This includes Andore Jr.'s bio states he practices many wrestling techniques with his brother and hopes to surpass him in fighting prowess. 

He does not do much of the talking, since he has a manager in the form of [[Poison (Final Fight)|]].

Hugo appears also in the [[street_fighter_iii_(series)|Street Fighter III: 3rd Strike]] videogame, as well as a Final Fight game called [i]Final Fight Revenge[/i].

title: ibuki_(street_fighter)
body:
[b]Ibuki[/b] ([b]いぶき / 息吹[/b], born December 6) is a character in the [[Street Fighter]] series. She first appeared in [[Street Fighter III (series)|]] and is voiced by Yuri Amano in all three games. She made her return in the prequel to that game, [[street fighter iv (series)|Super Street Fighter IV]].

Ibuki lives in a village composed entirely of [[Ninja]]. She has been trained from childhood, but resents her lot in life.

In Super Street Fighter IV, she sneaks away from her clan's summer training camp to compete in S.I.N's tournament, in order to meet cool and handsome guys. When the tournament is over, she realizes that she is late for camp and attempts to sneak back in as if nothing had happened. However, she is caught by one of the camp's instructors.

Later in 2nd Impact, Ibuki was sent by her clan to procure documents from [[Gill (street fighter)|]]'s organization. These documents concerned the "G-File" project, which was responsible for creating Necro and Twelve. Gill voluntarily gave Ibuki the documents, though the project was already under way by that point.

In [[street fighter iii (series)|3rd Strike]], Ibuki tracks down [[Oro (street fighter)|]] to fight him for her ninja graduation exam. She fights well enough to pass, and moves on to go to a university. While there, she joins a club which, to her dismay, turns out to be based on ninja training.

Gouken is most often depicted as an [[old man|elderly man]] with a white [[beard]] and [[prayer beads]] around his neck. In his most recent [[Street Fighter IV (series)|]] appearance, Gouken wears a single sleeved, Navy Blue colored karate gi and sports a long, white braid of hair adorned with a single prayer bead. 

Gouken plays an integral role in the series' backstory, and was first depicted as a picture in Akuma's ending in [[Street Fighter Zero (series)|Street Fighter Zero]]. Gouken's first actual appearance as a character was in Street Fighter IV, as a boss character. He is an unlockable character in the home console version of the game. He bears a strong resemblance to a character in one of the series rival games, [[Tekken]]'s [[Mishima Jinpachi]].

title: sodom
body:
[b]Sodom[/b] is a video game character from the both the [[Final Fight]] and [[Street Fighter]] series produced by [[Capcom]]. 

He first appeared in Final Fight. Sodom was renamed [b]Katana[/b] in the North American SNES version of Street Fighter Alpha 2 for name issues. He was a top member of the original Mad Gear gang. 

A Caucasian male born in the United States, Sodom is obsessed with Japanese culture and considers himself Japanese. He is well-versed in many elements of Japanese culture, though his usage of the language is somewhat dubious. 

In combat, Sodom wears tabi and geta, [[samurai]] gauntlets, blue jeans, body armor, and a samurai kabuto with a mask. 

On the front of his outfit, Sodom has scrawled the Japanese kanji shi (死), meaning death. However, this kanji is not written properly, and actually has no meaning. Sodom's failed attempt at Japanese calligraphy emblazoned across his chest at all times is meant to be humorous. 

He is never seen fighting without a pair of jitte or katana blades, making him one of the few characters to appear in the Street Fighter series to use weaponry. In the Japanese version of Final Fight, the katana are named Masamune and Muramasa.

title: murder_hornet
body:
Known as the Murder Hornet in the USA, due to its habit of attacking bee hives and beheading all the bees in the hive. 

https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Asian_giant_hornet
The Asian giant hornet (Vespa mandarinia) or northern giant hornet, including the color form referred to as the Japanese giant hornet, is the world's largest hornet. It is native to temperate and tropical East Asia, South Asia, Mainland Southeast Asia, and parts of the Russian Far East. It was also found in the Pacific Northwest of North America in late 2019 with a few more additional sightings in 2020, and nests found in 2021, prompting concern that it could become an invasive species.

title: islington_(mist_train_girls)
body:
Lady Islington Elrond is the fourth daughter of the Elrond family. She is known as the "Oracle Child", said to be chosen by St. Iris, the Goddess of the Clouds. Knights of the Order of St. Iris have been instructed in the ways of the sword and shield to give their lives to defend Islington. As stated by King's Cross, all knights in St. Iris are expected to kneel upon Her presence. Outside of her official duties however, Islington enjoys sneaking out in disguise and overhear others, as well as providing assistance where requested.

Lady Islington enjoys teasing her youngest sister Paddington, as the two are close in age. Just like her younger sister Paddington, she has a great liking for food all around the world. Personality wise, Islington can rapidly switch between joking, sarcasm and serious emotions.

First appeared in Chapter 14, Lady Islington shared some information on the true nature of the Mist, and requested help from the Conductor's team to assist her and King's Cross's individual research and enter the boundary of the World Tree to investigate the reasons behind the Sea of Mist, using information from both the Resistance and the Mistism cult.

Islington is very skilled in combat. Even without her personal assistant King's Cross, she's still capable of fighting toe-to-toe with Queenrose, thanks to the Goddess's blessings (though at the time Queenrose was also affected . Upon calling the powers of the Goddess, King's Cross has to cast an advanced defensive shield to keep the Mist Train intact. Islington also has the ability to grant iron injections, just like the Conductor.

title: exercise_bike
body:
A "stationary bicycle":[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stationary_bicycle] (also known as exercise bicycle, exercise bike, spinning bike, or exercycle) is a device used as exercise equipment for indoor cycling. It includes a saddle, pedals, and some form of handlebars arranged as on a (stationary) bicycle.

A stationary bicycle is usually a special-purpose exercise machine resembling a bicycle without wheels. It is also possible to adapt an ordinary bicycle for stationary exercise by placing it on bicycle rollers or a trainer. Rollers and trainers are often used by racing cyclists to warm up before racing, or to train on their own machines indoors.

title: help:favorite_groups
body:
Favorite groups are personal collections of posts. They're like tags or pools, except they belong to you. You can use them to organize your favorite posts, save [[comic]]s you plan to read or translate, to create your own private tags, or just to collect posts as you see fit.

Favorite groups are similar to [[help:pools|pools]] in that they are an ordered collection of posts that can be browsed through. The main difference is that favgroups are owned by a single user and that user is the only one who can add or remove posts from it.

h4. Viewing your favorite groups

Your favorite groups are listed under "Fav groups" in the menu on the main "/posts":/posts page, and under Statistics in your user profile.

You can search for favorite groups using the {{favgroup:<name>}} or {{favgroup:<id number>}} metatags (see [[help:cheatsheet]]).

h4. Adding a post to a favorite group

Click the "Add to favorite group" link in the sidebar, then select which group to add the post to (if you only have one group, you won't have to select which group to add to).

A shortcut is to press the "g" key to open the "Add to favorite group" dialog, then press a number key (1-9) to select a favorite group.

You may also tag a post with {{favgroup:<name>}} to add it to a favgroup. You can use [[help:tag scripts|tag scripting]] to quickly add posts to a favgroup in bulk.

h4. Removing a post from a favorite group

Tag the post with {{-favgroup:<name>}}. You can use [[help:tag scripts|tag scripting]] to quickly remove posts from a favgroup in bulk.

You may also edit the favgroup to remove posts from it. To edit a favgroup, go to the main "Posts page":[/posts], click "Fav groups" at the top, click on the favgroup in the list, then click "Edit" at the top of the page.

h4. Privacy

Favgroups are public by default. "Gold users":[/user_upgrades/new] and above can make their favorite groups private. To make a favgroup private, go to your "Fav groups page":/favorite_groups, click the favorite group you wish to make private, then click "Edit" at the top of the page and check the "Private" box.

h4. Limitations

Regular members may create up to 10 favgroups. Users of higher level have no restriction. See [[help:users]] for more info.

In addition, a single favorite group may have up to 10,000 posts.

title: academy_city
body:
Academy City is a landlocked sovereign city-state whose territory consists of a walled enclave within Western Tokyo. It is the primary setting of the [[Toaru Majutsu no Index]] series and its side stories.

As the city's name suggests, it is a city of several schools and institutions of higher learning from kindergarten to university level that learn side-by-side along with the scientists who research on psychic powers and higher technology, the latter being one of the primary reasons for its establishment. It is the most advanced city in the world and its technology is said to be 20 or 30 years ahead of the world. Academy City is composed of 23 districts, called School Districts which are simply numbered from one to twenty-three and each of these districts have a specific purpose.

In the novel series, there are only a handful of residents who know about magic, either due to encountering it or being part of the magic side themselves, such as [[Kamijou Touma]], [[Index (toaru majutsu no index)|Index]], [[Misaka Mikoto]], [[Accelerator (toaru majutsu no index)|Accelerator]], and [[Hamazura Shiage]].

[b]Shadow of the Colossus[/b] is a [[fantasy]] action and adventure [[video game]] created by Team ICO, directed and designed by Ueda Fumito. 

The 2nd game of the [[Ico]] series, Shadow of the Colossus revolves around the story of a young man traversing a forbidden land with his horse to slay several powerful colossi in order to revive a fallen maiden.

title: soul_calibur_(weapon)
body:
[b]Soul Calibur[/b] is a legendary weapon and the namesake of most entries in the [[Soulcalibur|Soul series]] of fighting games. Soul Calibur is a weapon of purity that is diametrically opposed to its sibling, the corruptive [[Soul Edge (weapon)|Soul Edge]]. The gleaming crystalline weapon - inhabited by the spirit [[Elysium (soulcalibur)|]], the opposite of Soul Edge's spirit Inferno - is singular in its purpose, focused solely on defeating Soul Edge by any means necessary. Despite its noble calling, it does not mean it is a benevolent weapon; it will attempt to make any sacrifice needed to starve Soul Edge of souls to claim, even if that includes ending all life on the planet by suspending its inhabitants in crystal or even trapping its wielder in crystal if it feels they are not up to the task. Like Soul Edge, it can take the form of whatever is most convenient for its current owner.

Soul Calibur's most famous owners include [[Chai Xianghua]] (without her knowledge at the time), [[Siegfried Schtauffen]] after forsaking the moniker of [[Nightmare (Soulcalibur)|Nightmare]], and [[Patroklos Alexander]].

title: danmaku
body:
[i]For the card game of the same name, see [[Danmaku!!]][/i]
弾幕 (lit. "Barrage")

Mode of attack used by enemies in some shooting games. Complex attack patterns, made of hundreds to thousands of projectiles fill the screen. The player must weave through tiny gaps in the barrage. End-stage boss attacks are especially spectacular, in an attempt to intimidate and dazzle the player.

Danmaku are usually made of missiles, but are sometimes combined with other hazards such as lasers, flames and lightning arcs for added challenge. 

Missiles in danmaku have been particularly creative of late, most notably in the [[Touhou]] series. Throwing knives, flower petals, paper charms and even ghosts have been employed in addition to the usual shells and colored balls.

This tag is used to refer to depictions of attacks launched by  characters or weapons from known shooting games.

h4. See also

* [[Touhou]]
* [[Danmaku comments]] - a unique scrolling comments system created by [[Niconico]], named after this attack

title: vrlitwhai_kridanik
body:
[b]Vrlitwhai Kridanik[/b] (ブリタイ・クリダニク, [i]Buritai Kuridaniku[/i]) is a character from the [[MACROSS]] universe. He appears in [[choujikuu_yousai_macross|The Super Dimension Fortress Macross]], [[Macross: Do You Remember Love?]], and [[Macross Flashback 2012]]. 

Vrlitwhai is a [[Zentradi]] fleet commander in charge of his own fleet under the [[Boddole Zer]] Main Fleet. His command post is a [[Nupetiet-Vergnitzs]] [[spacecraft]]. 

As a commander-type Zentradi, he is much larger and stronger than the normal Zentradi [[soldier]], and can even survive in the vacuum of [[space]] for limited periods of time, allowing him to go toe to toe with a [[VF-1]].

The original Japanese romanization of the character's name, according to Studio Nue, is "[b]Vrlitwhai Kridanik[/b]". The creators of Macross originally gave this and other Zentradi character names unusual romanizations to befit their [[alien]] nature.

The name of the character was changed to [b]Vrlitwhai 7018[/b] in the [i]Do You Remember Love?[/i] anime film and to [b]Breetai[/b] in the [[ROBOTECH]] American adaptation.

The visual design of this character is based on [[Domel]] from the [[Uchuu Senkan Yamato]] anime series.

title: de_havilland_vampire
body:
The [b]de Havilland DH.100 Vampire[/b] was a British subsonic fighter [[jet]] developed and manufactured by the [i]de Havilland[/i] British jet company. Having been developed during the Second World War to harness the newly developed jet engine, the Vampire entered service with the Royal Air Force (RAF) in 1945. 

The Royal Air Force used the Vampire as a front line fighter until 1953 before it assumed secondary roles such as pilot training. It was retired by the RAF in 1966. It achieved several aviation firsts and records, including being the first jet aircraft to cross the Atlantic Ocean. 

The Vampire had many export sales and was operated by various air forces. Almost 3,300 Vampires were manufactured, a quarter of them built under license in several countries. Some of its former operators were [[Canada]], [[Austria]], [[Norway]], [[New Zealand]], [[Japan]], [[Mexico]], [[Venezuela]], etc.

It participated in subsequent conflicts such as the 1948 Arab–Israeli War, the Malayan emergency and the Rhodesian Bush War.

title: bf_110
body:
The Messerschmitt Bf-110 [i]Zerstörer[/i] ("Destroyer") was a twin-engined, twin-tailed heavy fighter used by Luftwaffe during [[wwwii|World War II]]. Originally designed as a three-seat escort and interdiction [[aircraft]], its poor showing in the "Battle of Britain":http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_Britain against single-engined fighters like the [[supermarine spitfire|Supermarine Spitfire]] and [[hawker hurricane|Hawker Hurricane]] relegated it to other roles. It went on to serve in many theaters as a night fighter, bomber interceptor, and attack aircraft.

The Bf-110 commonly carried whatever was considered a "heavy gun" at the time in its nose (2 20mm or 30mm cannon, later including an optional undernose gun pod). Early models were able to carry 4 250kg bombs on the outer wings, while later versions could carry two 250kg or 500kg bombs near the wing roots. Some versions meant for bomber interception also carried two or four "WGr21":http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Werfer-Granate_21 air-to-air rockets.

title: fw_190
body:
A [[World War II|World War II]] German fighter-bomber produced by Focke-Wulf Flugzeugbau AG. It had wide-track landing gear and a rearward-sliding raised canopy. Initial models had a short, tightly cowled nose housing a "radial engine":http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radial_engine; later ones (the D and Ta 152 series) had longer noses with liquid-cooled inline engines (see post #520843 for a comparison). They also had lengthened fuselages and longer wings. 

The Fw 190 could carry combinations of nose- and wing-mounted 13mm [[machine_gun|machine guns]] and/or 20mm [[cannon]]. Some had a 30mm [i]Motorkanone[/i] firing through the propeller hub, while the ground attack versions could carry rockets or bombs. The [i]Würger[/i] ("Shrike" or "Butcher Bird") could also carry external fuel tanks.

title: tales_of_the_abyss
body:
The eighth mothership title in Namco's [[tales of (series)|Tales Series]]. Devolped by [[Tales of Symphonia|Team Symphonia]], Tales of the Abyss follows the story of the young, secluded noble, [[Luke fon Fabre]], on a journey of political and religious intrigue that changes his attitude about himself and other people for the better. It was released in Japan on the [[Playstation 2]] on December 15, 2005, and in North America on October 10, 2006.

Recently received a straight [[Nintendo 3DS]] port in Japan on June 30, 2011, and was released for the first time in Europe on November 24, 2011. The North American version of the 3DS port was later released on [[valentine|Feburary 14]], 2012.
